^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Very nice Bonnie :). A few things to discuss. First of all, the 1N bid by bonnie. Sometimes you have to bid 1N with a singleton in responder's suit, but that is a white lie. You really are supposed to have NT distribution. For example, if Bonnie had 1 spade 4 hearts 5 diamonds and 3 clubs, her only choices of rebid are 1N or 2D.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And unless her diamonds are really good, 1N is usually better. But, on this hand, she has 4 clubs. So 2C is a more descriptive bid, and does not misrepresent her hand. So, although 1N would be my 2nd choice, I think 2C is slightly better. The one time I might bid 1N with Bonnie's distribution is if I had 4 little clubs.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to the opening lead. Normally 4th from longest is best but not if the opponents bid the suit and granted East's next best suit is clubs. But leading from AQx is very dangerous. And it is not even clear which one to lead. In suits you never lead away from an Ace but in NT you often do.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, should Boater choose to lead clubs, any of the 3 cards could be right. as that is not a suit you usually lead from. I would have probably led a heart with her hand, but a club could be right if pard had say the @CJ.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT|^B@2
boater: Why is it so dangerous?|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example on this hand, you have the @cAQ behind the @CKing. You gave up a trick by setting up Bonnie's @CKing.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me briefly discuss Checkback Stayman, which is an alternative to New Minor Forcing, and what I prefer. I know most people play New Minor Forcing, but I am not sure why they think it is better. |
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Checkback works as over a 1N rebid, 2C is always "Checkback Stayman", even if opener had opened 1C. Checkback Stayman asks the same question as New Minor Forcing, that is "Partner do you have either 3 card support for my major (bid my suit) or 4 cards in the other major (bid that sit)."|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If opener has neither, then opener rebids 2D rather than 2N (as in NMF) and that is an advantage over NMF. It gives the Checkback bidder a lot more flexibility. For example I could bid 2H on some hands, asking Bonnie to pick between 2H and 2S, or I could bid 2S to play, or I could bid 2N, which I would have on this hand asking Bonnie to bid 3N with a good 13 or 14.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|With New Minor Forcing, I have a problem over Bonnie's 2N bid. I have to guess whether or not to bid 3N. That is why I like Checkback Stayman -- it makes for much more flexible auctions.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Noah121:  Can NMF or Checkback be used after a 2NT rebid?|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yes Checkback and NMF both apply after a 2N rebid. But you cannot play both. You have to choose between Checkback and NMF. On BBO, NMF is much more popular which is why I brought it up.|
